Germany first in Europe introduces "indefinite sex" when registering children
Germany will be the first country in Europe to allow "indefinite" children born with hermaphrodites to be registered as children born to hermaphrodites.
The child's parents will have the right to leave the "sex" on the birth certificate unfilled for a while.
Instead of "F" (female) or "M" (male), parents can write "X" (indefinite) for a while.
This decision is aimed at not encouraging parents to hurry with the operation to "clarify" the sex.
According to statistics, one in 2,000 newborns in the world is born hermaphrodite.
Anger over Bali terror attack organisers' verdict
Survivors and relatives of the 202 people killed in the 2002 Bali bombing reacted angrily to the verdict handed down by the last of the conspirators, who was tried and said Umar Patek should be shot.
Patek, who spent nearly 10 years on the run as one of the most wanted men in Southeast Asia, was yesterday sentenced to 20 years in prison for his role in creating the explosive devices used in the attack.
He could be released within 15 years if he was granted parole.
The 45-year-old defendant was found guilty of mass murder in an attack on two nightclubs in the popular tourist district of Kuta, in which 202 people were killed, including 88 Australians, and dozens more were injured.
He was also found guilty of a number of other terrorism-related charges, including a spate of church bombings across Indonesia on Christmas Eve in 2000.
Prosecutors have demanded a life sentence, though they could insist that a man dubbed a "subversive" for his reputation as a bomb maker should be sentenced to death.
The decision compounded the painful memories of Perth mother June Cortines, who lost her 39-year-old twin daughters Jane and Jenny in a terror attack carried out by Patek and his accomplices almost a decade ago.
Barely holding back tears, she said Patek should have been sentenced to death.
"I really think he should follow in the footsteps of the other guys.
He should be brought before the firing squad," Ms Cortines told AAP.
"I have to live every day knowing that I will no longer have grandchildren and I will not see my daughters."
The Sari Club was destroyed when a massive explosive device was detonated in a van parked outside just after 11pm on 12 October 2002.
Peter Hughes was at the Paddy Bar, where a suicide bomber detonated a backpack packed with explosives just 20 seconds earlier.
After the attack, he fell into a coma for a month and "died" three times, being connected to the life support system.
Mr Hughes said Patek should share the fate of three other members of the Jemaah Islamiyah terrorist cell responsible for the massacre- Amrozi, Mukhlas and Imam Samudra, who were executed four years ago.
Indeed, this guy deserves the death penalty the most.
To keep him alive, well, there's no reason to keep him alive.
Getting 20 years after killing 202 people and injuring hundreds is not that much.
Patek is the latest member of the Bali terror attack to stand trial.
He had been in hiding for nearly a decade, but was eventually detained in January 2011 in the Pakistani city of Abbottabad, where U.S. troops killed former al-qaeda leader Osama bin Laden less than four months later.
During the trial, an FBI agent testified that intelligence evidence showed that Patek was in Pakistan to meet with bin Laden in an attempt to re-establish ties between the terrorist groups of Southeast Asia and Al-Kaida.
"He didn't give up," Ms. Cortines said.
Until recently, he had no regrets about how much grief he had caused other people.
The verdict comes ahead of the 10th anniversary of the terror attack, which will be celebrated later this year in Bali and Australia.
"There will be a lot of tears this year," Ms. Cortines said.
Patek can still appeal his sentence.
