Cocaine-addicted lawyer who alerted ringleader of criminal gang to police investigation jailed
Basharat Ditta, 42, passed on information to crime boss Neil Scarborough
Lawyer feared his secret drug addiction would be uncovered
He was sentenced to three years in prison by Liverpool Crown Court.
A prestigious lawyer who told a drug lord about a major police investigation because he feared exposing his secret drug addiction has been jailed for three years.
Basharat Ditta, 42, gave criminal authority Neil Scarborough classified information about an investigation into his drug trafficking activities after he was threatened by his cocaine addiction.
The lawyer, nicknamed Bash and dubbed "cool lawyer among the offenders," was arrested at his home in 2011 after a police operation to spy on Scarborough, whom he had previously represented in a drug trial.
Officers noticed that 32-year-old Scarborough had left three bags of cocaine outside the lawyer's home in Blackburn, Lancashire, while he was at a law association dinner with colleagues.
The inquest heard that Ditta "regularly used" the Class A drug after tests showed traces of cocaine in his hair, on his wallet and on credit cards.
During the eight months from January to August 2011, he tried to illegally obtain information about the arrests of two men on behalf of Scarborough, as well as one of his accomplices.
All four suspects were under police surveillance at the time as part of a major investigation into the activities of a criminal heroin and cocaine trafficking organisation in Lancashire, Cumbria, Merseyside, Berkshire and West Yorkshire.
They and 32 others were later jailed after police seized heroin and cocaine in a series of raids, amounting to £1.5 million, as well as more than £200,000 in cash.
Ditta, 42, passed on information to criminals out of fear that his cocaine addiction would be uncovered.
Today at Liverpool Crown Court, Ditt, who works for the law firm Forbes Solicitors in Blackburn, was shamed after pleading guilty to two counts of intentional obstruction of justice following a three-week trial at Liverpool Crown Court.
He admitted possession of cocaine at an earlier court hearing.
The lawyer's revelation came after police investigating Scarborough revealed that he had spoken to Ditt regularly by phone since February 2011.
Two detectives followed the suspect and found him walking up to Ditt's home in Blackburn and placing the 60 per cent purity drugs in a black golf glove under the lawyer's bins.
Shortly after the transfer, Scarborough repeatedly called up WithItt, who was at dinner at Blackburn Rovers' Ewood Park football stadium.
The lawyer returned home for drugs; nine conversations took place between them.
The court heard that Ditta "regularly used" cocaine after tests found traces of the Class A drug in his hair, wallet and on his credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested but denied using cocaine, said he had spoken to the suspected dealer because he was his client, and insisted their communication was a "lawyer's secret."
During his detention, Ditt took his wallet and tried to take out several credit cards, but all of them were confiscated, and a hair sample was also taken from him.
When questioned by the police, he said that along with the workplace, he had a home office and clients came to his house for legal reasons.
However, the court heard that after the important arrests, he called the largest participants in drug trafficking, a number of whom he had previously represented in court, to tell them what detectives knew about them.
In the indictment, Anne White said, "If anyone knows that the law should not be broken, it is a criminal lawyer."
Mr. Ditt is accused of abusing his position as a criminal lawyer because he had entered into too close a relationship with certain clients.
The contact we are talking about is not just a drug dealer, but a drug dealer supplying drugs to his own lawyer.
Some of his conversations will certainly prove legitimate because he was their lawyer.
However, this has largely crossed the boundaries of the usual lawyer-client relationship.
He obstructed the police investigation as much as possible to allow these individuals to continue their criminal activities.
Mr. Ditt did not honor his profession, but shamed her.
He became too close to certain clients, in particular Scarborough, and allowed to doubt his disinterest.
Ditta pleaded not guilty and said: "If I was a corrupt lawyer, of which I am not, and I would like to pass on information to Mr. Scarborough, I would not have waited 15 hours, I would have done so immediately."
But after the hearing, senior officer Lee Halstead, of Lancashire Police, said: "Mr Ditta went from being a criminal lawyer to a criminal as soon as he started buying drugs from organised crime."
His addiction to cocaine made him hopelessly compromised and vulnerable to the purposes of the main members of the criminal gangs, who entrusted him with obtaining valuable information about police investigations.
Lawyers must follow the highest standards of professional ethics and inspire trust and confidence in society.
Mr. Ditt betrayed that trust and tried to hide behind his profession.
The investigation into Mr Ditt led the Lancashire Specially Dangerous Organised Crime Unit, which has already succeeded him in three counts of cocaine possession and now obstruction of justice, demonstrating our desire to ensure fair punishment for offenders.
Let this case serve as a warning to criminals that no one is beyond the reach of the law.
We'll find you and bring you to justice.
Scarborough himself was sentenced to 14 years after pleading guilty to conspiracy to supply heroin, cocaine and marijuana.
