Jet manufacturers feud over seat width when big orders at stake
A bitter dispute has erupted between major aircraft manufacturers over the width of tourist class seats on long-haul flights, setting the tone for a fierce confrontation at this month's Dubai Aviation Show.
The dispute revolves around the width of seats provided on long-haul flights to economy class passengers whose interests are not always the focus of airlines, while the amount of space allocated to them plays a key role in the approval of the latest aircraft offered by Airbus SAS and Boeing Co.
Airbus this week called for the introduction of an industry standard that would provide seat width of at least 18 inches (46 cm) in economy-class cabins, but its main U.S. competitor Boeing says it should be up to airlines.
The dispute comes at a time when aircraft manufacturers are competing in sales of increasingly large versions of their twin-engine long-haul aircraft, with potentially record-breaking orders expected at the November 17-21 event.
The layout of the rear of the aircraft - especially whether 9 or 10 people are sitting in a row - is central to the statements about the economic effectiveness of the new "mini-airbus" projects.
Boeing says its revamped 777X will accommodate 406 people, based on seats in economy class of more than 17 inches wide, placed 10 in each row.
Airbus says the rival version of its A350 will carry 350 people in economy class on 18-inch-wide seats, 9 in a row.
The giants of the aircraft industry often exchange blows on technical issues through advertising in the professional press.
And now Airbus is addressing the public before the Dubai Airshow, where the 777X is expected to become a leader with more than 100 orders.
She recently demonstrated what a new advertising war could be like by showing financiers a slide depicting three people in a restaurant huddled together, titled "Would you agree to that?"
"Boeing offers long-haul flights on seats narrower than regional turboprop aircraft," said Airbus sales manager John Leahy.
With the change in diet, people are gaining weight, but the aircraft seats have not changed dramatically.
Between the early 1970s, when the wide-body Boeing 747 set standards for modern long-haul travel, and the century-old weight of the average American male aged 40 to 49 increased by 10 percent, according to the U.S. Department of Health.
The waist girth of the average 21st century American male is 39.7 inches, according to U.S. health statistics.
Airbus claims that its competitor adheres to the concept of seats of the 1950s, when the average waist girth of those recently called "reactive public" was already.
Airbus says it has commissioned a study showing that an extra inch of seat width improves sleep quality by 53 percent.
Boeing disputes Airbus's seat size figures and says manufacturers should not interfere with decisions about how airlines balance fares and amenities.
According to her, studies show that the convenience of the cabin depends not only on the width of the seat.
"It really comes down to giving airlines the choice and the ability to do what they think they need to do to succeed," said Boeing cabin specialist Kent Craver.
They don't want us to decide for them what will make them profit.
They know their business better than anyone else.
For passengers, the issue is to increase space on the sides, but for suppliers it is increasingly becoming a factor that can affect profits.
Behind this dispute is the race for orders for planes valued at at least $700 billion at catalytic prices in the coming decades - enough to change the ratio of U.S. to European exports.
As Reuters first reported in July, seating is exactly what fuels the rivalry in the battle between the newest jets.
