"The reason Boeing is doing this is to cram more seats and make its aircraft more competitive than our development," said Kevin Keniston, Airbus's head of passenger comfort in Europe.
On the other hand, analysts say that cabins with full 10-seater rows for the existing 777s indicate that many passengers prefer a tight seating that can go hand in hand with lower fares.
"Eighteen-inch seats would be ideal for passengers, but the reality is that from a commercial point of view, Airbus's offer is driven by the threat posed by the 777 model," said salon interior designer Mary Kirby, founder and editor of runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not supply seats, but offer a catalogue of suppliers from which airlines can choose.
The world-travelling jet sellers even carry roulette to check competing layouts.
Touting comfort, all manufacturers also offer aircraft with a very dense layout of cabin for budget airlines and regional flights.
Airbus offers the A350 with 10-seater rows, but says it hasn't sold it yet.
Until recently, Airbus emphasized the need for additional cabin modifications, offering more seats at the aisle on some of its aircraft.
Without the support of the only other manufacturer of large modern aircraft, experts say, its call for a new industry standard is unlikely to "take off", but may divert attention from the wave of sales of the 777X model.
