Security concerns in Mozambique grow as powerful people clash
Under a top-down statue of Samora Machel, Mozambique's founding president, thousands of people gathered in downtown Maputo to chant slogans about peace at one of the rare demonstrations here.
"We want the return of peace; we want stability," said Vanessa de Susa, chief executive of the investment company.
Fearing for her country's future, she swapped the business suit for a T-shirt emblazoned with the words "We demand security" in Portuguese, and joined the crowd in the capital's Independence Square on Thursday.
For two weeks, there have been almost daily reports of clashes between government forces and Renamo, one of the most violent skirmishes since the truce was signed more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a well-known rebel movement, supported first by the white authorities of Rhodesia and then by the apartheid-era South African government as part of efforts to destabilize the country's independent government.
After the 1992 armistice, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe that the country is unlikely to slide back into full-blown conflict, but recent events have made foreign investors and locals nervous.
The stakes are high for a fast-growing economy because the discovery of huge offshore gas reserves and coal deposits in the Northwest could attract more than $50 billion in investments in the next few years from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale of Brazil, Eni from Italy and Anadarko from the US.
Frelimo's ruling party, a leading political force since 1975, and renamo party blame each other for the tensions.
Renamo's party claims the government has been the instigator of recent clashes, attacking its members in Sofala province, the traditional stronghold of Renamo, on October 17.
Attacks on former rebels then escalated when government forces attacked Renamo bases and tried to kill Afonso Dhlakama, the group's leader, Fernando Mazanga, a spokesman for Renamo, told the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo for initiating the clashes, accusing the party of attacking soldiers.
President Armando Gebuza tried to allay fears of instability.
Gebuza told AFP, a French news agency, on Wednesday that Mr. Dhakama felt like a "loser" who wanted to use "everything left of his forces to try to prove that he could impose his own decisions on the government."
Both Frelimo and Renamo insist that they want to avoid war.
However, fears grew after reports that Mazanga had announced Renamo's rejection of the 1992 peace agreement.
He told the Financial Times that he was referring to frelimo's non-compliance with the agreement.
"Our goal is to return to the negotiations, but in all seriousness," Mazanga said.
Previous talks between the parties have done little to ease tensions, which have been exacerbated by a series of clashes this year.
"These are two powerful people (Gebuza and Dhlakama) who have faced their foreheads," said Joseph Hanlon, a lecturer at the Open University and an expert on Mozambique.
None of them is a good negotiator and none of them are ready to make the necessary concessions.
Renamo's party, which is trying to push for electoral reforms, has already announced that it will boycott municipal elections scheduled for Nov.
Presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators interpreted this pressure as an attempt by the weakened movement to secure concessions and financial bonuses from the government.
The share of votes for Renamo has been declining since 1992, while the new party, the Mozambique Democratic Movement (MDM), founded by former Renamo member, is expected to improve its performance in this election.
Mr. Mazanga said that Mr. Gebuza, who is due to step down next year when his second term ends, wants to destroy democracy in the country.
"He doesn't want multi-party democracy, he doesn't want transparent elections, he doesn't want peace because he doesn't want to leave the presidency," Mazanga said.
It is not clear what capabilities Renamo has, but it has already carried out devastating and rapid attacks on police stations and cars on a key north-south highway.
Most of the skirmishes took place in Sofala province, which is a few hundred kilometers north of Maputo, but includes Beira, a port that mining companies including Rio Tinto and Vale use to export coal.
In June, Rio suspended the use of railway tracks for about a week after Renamo threatened to attack the railway.
Mazanga was evasive when asked if Renamo would repeat the threat.
Renamo's party wanted to "warn the international community that things are not going well in Mozambique," Mazanga said.
Instability has increased dissatisfaction with the government, and many people are also concerned about corruption, slow pace of development and the recent increase in kidnappings, said Fernando Lima, head of the independent media company Mediacoop.
"People think that the government and the president are responsible for the future of the country, and they have to find a solution to these problems," he says.
Omar Sultouan, a participant in the demonstration, said people just wanted stability.
"Nobody cares about Renamo or Frelimo, they just want a resumption of peace, they want free access to roads," he said.
Rules for the use of electronic devices on aircraft in Australia will remain in force for the time being
Australian airline passengers will be required to continue to turn off their tablets and smartphones during take-off and landing, despite measures in the US to relax the rules on these devices.
The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration has allowed U.S. carriers to change their procedures so that passengers can read e-books, watch videos or play games on their devices during takeoff and landing, provided they remain in "Flight Mode."
Passengers can already do this during the main part of the flight, but many are annoyed that they do not have access to their e-books during take-off and landing.
Australian carriers are considering the decision, which required US airlines to do a huge amount of work to meet the new requirements, but said they had no plans to change their procedures in the near future.
The Civil Aviation Safety Authority also said it was reviewing the application, but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices in critical flight phases were still in place in Australia.
"The Civil Aviation Safety Authority does not currently have specific rules governing the use of electronic devices in aircraft," it said.
This issue is governed by rules that require air carriers to maintain safety at all times, and passengers to comply with safety rules reported to them by crew members.
Virgin, which has already discussed with the Civil Aviation Safety Authority the expansion of its Wi-Fi entertainment system on board, was not opposed to the changes but said it would follow the regulator's instructions.
"We would welcome the Civil Aviation Safety Authority's consideration of allowing the use of electronic devices because we really think it will improve the quality of customer service now that it (the on-board wireless entertainment system) is on our aircraft," the spokesman said.
It said it would abide by the current rules.
"Our current policy is that electronic devices cannot be used during take-off and landing, and we do not plan to change them any time soon," she said.
The FAA's ruling applies to U.S. airlines.
Nevertheless, we are always interested in regulatory changes that could benefit passengers, and we will certainly look closely at the FAA's decision and the reasons for it.
For U.S. carriers, the impact of the order will vary from airline to airline and will depend on the age of their fleet.
Carriers will have to prove that their aircraft are resistant to radio-phones from mobile devices, as well as review manuals, training materials, carry-on baggage regulations and instructions for passengers.
"Once the airline checks and confirms its fleet's interference, it can allow passengers to use portable, lightweight electronic devices such as tablets, e-books and smartphones at any altitude," the FAA said.
In rare cases of poor visibility, the crew will instruct passengers to turn off their devices during landing.
In addition, according to the group's recommendation, heavier devices should be located under the seats or in the upper hold during take-off and landing.
