Scientists have shed light on how the movements of a dog's tail are related to its mood.
Earlier studies have shown that satisfied dogs wag their tails to the right side (from the dog's point of view), while alarmed dogs wave their tail predominantly to the left side.
But now scientists say that other members of the canine family may notice these subtle differences in tail wagging and react to them.
Professor Giorgio Wallortigara, a neuroscientist at Trent University, says: "It is well known that in humans the left and right sides of the brain are different in shaping the stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions."
Here we tried to look at it in other species.
He added that just like humans, dogs have the right side of the brain controlling the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the versatile tail-twisting of other dogs, researchers watched the animals as they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
We'll probably find out soon why their tails sometimes go one way and sometimes the other way.
Professor Wallortigara said: "We showed dogs videos of dogs - either naturalistic versions or silhouettes - to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the movement of the tail and direct the tail more left or right."
When the animals saw that otherwise the non-expressing dog was moving the tail to the right (in terms of the dog's wagging tail), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was leaning mostly to the left (again in terms of the dog's wagging tail), their heartbeat increased and they looked alarmed.
Professor Wallortigara said he did not think the dogs intentionally communicated with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from their experience what movements they should worry about and which ones they shouldn't.
He notes: "If there are several encounters with other dogs and often the waging of their tail to one side is associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, the dog reacts on the basis of this experience."
Researchers say these results could give owners, veterinarians and trainers a better understanding of their animal's emotions.
Dog behaviour expert John Bradshaw, a visiting research fellow at the University of Bristol Veterinary School, said this was not the first study to test whether the left and right sides mattered to dogs.
Last year, a team of scientists at the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads left when looking at an aggressive dog, and right when looking at a happy dog.
And in another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: "Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when its tail was wagging to the left rather than to the right, rather than becoming alarmed - the opposite of the behaviour towards the Italian study."
He said the differences could be because dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in films or robot dogs as dogs.
It might be useful to study how dogs respond to real dogs, he explained.
"While there is ample evidence for different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details have yet to be clarified, and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, we will probably soon see why their tails sometimes go one way and sometimes the other.
