Ride through mud, rivers and jungle to provide free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwell provides free medical care in rural Cameroon
Bwell and his team spend almost every weekend taking hundreds of patients
There are not many doctors in this West African country - only one in 5,000 people
Vote here or through your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwell is one of CNN's top 10 characters in 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 main characters to become CNN Hero of the Year.
This man will receive $250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwell saw his father return to life and fall unconscious again, wandering around hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaounde, Cameroon's capital.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but the infection spread to his brain and caused a hematoma, which reminded him of himself for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," said Georges Bwell.
If we had the money, we'd take him out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwell accompanied his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals for years, receiving any treatment they could receive.
"It's not easy," Bwell said.
"You can leave home at 5am, run to the hospital to be the first, but you are not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some may die because they have to wait.
The situation hasn't changed much since Bwell's father passed away in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor per 5,000 people in Cameroon.
By comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 people.
And even if Cameroonians could see a doctor, many of them would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of health spending there is private.
"Their only problem is poverty," Bwell said.
"And because of poverty, they can't enjoy their lives."
Seeing the suffering of his father and so many of his compatriots, Bwell was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Bwell and his team of volunteers performed 700 free operations.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at Yaounde Central Hospital.
He also founded asCOVIME, a non-profit organization that organizes weekend trips to the countryside to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have assisted nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 others are crammed into vans, tied to rooftops with medical supplies and travel across rough terrain to visit villages in need.
They are not always lucky.
More than once they had to push cars through rivers and mud.
But when they come, they are greeted like real heroes: it is a holiday with songs and dances and the best rooms that the locals can offer.
Free medical care in these villages is really an occasion for celebration, and Bwell with his broad smile and boundless energy is more than happy to join in the fun.
The next morning, the team begins to receive hundreds of patients.
"We welcome 500 people on every trip," Bwell said.
They come from all over the area within a 60 kilometer radius of the village and they come on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides a variety of medical services.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates - documents needed for school that many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evenings, the team performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually carried out in a school building, municipality or in a house; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the postoperative zone to make room for the next person.
Using a generator to light the operating and sanitary treatment equipment, Bwell and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
This is an unbearable pace, but the determination of the brigade usually helps to support the village musicians.
"They beat the drums all night so we could stay awake and keep working," Bwell said.
On Sunday, the brigade members head back to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and international medical students, has performed 700 free surgeries in the past year and they know that their help can make a huge difference to those they help.
One person explained that the free hernia surgery he had received would allow him to work again.
"It will change the future for me and my family," the man said.
In addition to these weekend clinical appointments and hospital work, Bwell's surgeon also works nights in private medical clinics around Yaounde.
It is this second job, he said, that provides 60% of the funding for his nonprofit organization; the rest are covered by private donations.
"I don't even know when he's sleeping," said Kathy O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer with the Bwell group.
He's always either in the hospital or trying to make money for the organization so that he can continue these campaigns.
For future doctors and nurses like O'Malley coming from the U.S. and Europe to join Bwell in his tasks, this is an opportunity for practice they would never have received at home.
"We were able to assist in surgeries where we helped remove blood stains or hold tools for Dr. Bwell," O'Malley said.
As a sophomore, you would never get that opportunity in America.
Volunteer students usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medicines.
But upon arrival in Yaounde, their food, transport and training are paid for by Bwell.
"He's a hero, no doubt about it," O'Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwell, almost constant workload is not an ordeal.
Helping others live a happy life, fulfilling the promise made to your father is what brings him great joy.
"I'm so happy when I do this job," Bwell said.
And I'm thinking about my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do this to make people laugh to reduce their pain.
Visit asCOVIME and see how you can help.
