Goldman Sachs warns of risks to Russian economy
Goldman Sachs has warned of growing risks to the main driver of Russia's fragile economic growth - consumption.
This is primarily a crisis of non-payments on unsecured consumer loans and massive reductions in workers.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed, but rather the structure of that growth.
Recently, it is completely conditioned by consumption, which almost does not slow down," said Clemens Graf, chief economist of Goldman Sachs for Russia, presenting yesterday the quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
Now nominal wage growth in Russia is about 10%.
With an inflation rate of 6%, it will be able to provide future consumer demand at about the current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is falling, so most likely, they will deal with optimization of personnel costs.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages grow by 10%, then GDP - only by 2%, - explained Mr. Graf.
Companies have faced a decline in profitability.
If it does not grow, it could lead to layoffs and higher unemployment.
Russian business cannot not raise salaries, commented Vladimir Pantyushin, chief economist at Barclays Capital for Russia and CIS.
Unemployment is near historic lows, competition for workers is high.
In order to lure employees from outside or to keep the current ones, employers have to raise salaries.
Consumption in Russia is supported by a very rapid growth in consumer credit.
According to Mr. Graf, because of the extremely high rates on consumer loans, this type of lending does not have a multiplier effect on the country's economy.
"We have not seen any benefits for the economy from the growth of consumer credit, the money does not diverge on the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments," the economist said.
But the problem is another - Goldman Sachs expects an increase in arrears on unsecured loans.
They are taken mainly by poor people who have nothing to provide.
Interest on such loans is high.
As a result, they are often not returned," Mr. Grafe said.
Therefore, the second threat to the growth of the economy in Russia - a possible crisis of non-payment on unsecured loans.
Vasily Solodkov, director of the HSE Banking Institute, is already seeing signs of an impending banking crisis.
Small credit organizations, without access to cheap resources, as state banks have, were forced to attract the funds of the population at high interest rates.
In response, state banks took to the war and began to reduce credit rates, - the economist continues.
Small credit organizations cannot issue loans at the same interest rates, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If state banks do not refuse dumping, Russia faces a full-fledged banking crisis, believes Vasily Solodkov.
The economist considers the deprivation of licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks a harbinger of mass collapse.
"The state banks themselves will not cope with this situation: the deposit insurance system was not originally designed for a systemic crisis," the head of the institute warns.
But the growth of consumption will slow down without the crisis of non-payments, according to the investment bank - because of the refusal to index salaries of civil servants and military, laid down in the current version of the draft budget.
Part of the impact on consumption will be mitigated by the freezing of tariffs of natural monopolies (and, as a result, by a decrease in inflation).
But only partially: if the investment does not grow (and there are no prerequisites for this yet - see reference), consumption growth will still slow down, according to Goldman Sachs.
Vladimir Pantyushin of Barclays Capital does not yet see the prerequisites for implementing pessimistic scenarios.
"The main risk is still the fall in the price of oil," he says.
According to his estimation, the Russian economy will begin to shrink at the cost of oil below $90/barrel.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the Central Bank is not yet able to reduce interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation has decreased, and banks began to raise rates.
This may mean that they did not believe the Central Bank, which announced the transition to inflation targeting," Clemens Grafet said.
The interest policy of the Central Bank does not affect market rates, affects only the rates of interbank lending.
"For the Central Bank, this is the collapse of all hopes," Clemens Graf said.
The money received at the central bank's auctions is used by banks not to lend to the economy, but to manage their liquidity
As soon as the rate decreases, the exchange rate changes immediately, it means that the funds are trying to go on speculation against the ruble.
"Sooner or later, the Central Bank will understand that this strategy does not work," said Mr. Graf, who reminded that the state plans to let the ruble into "free float" by the end of 2015.
But we will either have to do it earlier or raise the key rate of the Central Bank (5.5%), he believes.
According to his estimation, the ruble exchange rate is now artificially inflated by 10%.
The ruble has only one road - to weaken - the expert concludes.
But if the Central Bank casts in financiers even a shadow of doubt that the liquidation of the currency corridor is not part of the policy to weaken the ruble, it can bring down the ruble much more strongly.
