"Depending on the status of the plan, we could approve the expansion of electronic devices very soon," the FAA said.
Passengers are now required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the plane door closes.
They must not restart them until the plane reaches an altitude of 10,000 feet and the captain gives "goodness."
Passengers should turn off their devices again when the plane is dropping for landing, and do not turn them on until the plane is on the ground.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected from electronic interference can allow passengers to use these devices during takeoff, landing and taxiing, the FAA said.
Most of the new airliners and other aircraft modified so that passengers can use Wi-Fi at high altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glaiding, president of the Association of Professional Flight Attendants, welcomed the changes.
"Once the new policy is implemented safely (and we are going to work closely with the carrier to achieve this), it will be a win-win option," Glaiding said.
We are frankly tired of feeling "on duty at school" when it comes to this issue.
But Internet connectivity for surfing, email exchange, text messaging or data downloads will still be banned at a height of less than 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will be asked to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to airplane mode.
Thus, there is still no "Words with Friends" - an intelligent internet game, which actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when there was a sensational case: the actor was removed from the American Airlines plane for refusing to turn off the device while the plane was at the gate.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, will still need to be stowed in the luggage compartment as they can injure someone if they fly all over the cabin.
Calls from mobile phone in-flight will also continue to be banned.
The regulatory powers over phone calls belong to the Federal Communications Commission, not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on some electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert at CBS News, said cell phones are still considered a risk.
"Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they can potentially interfere with navigation devices, but we know through the FCC that they can interfere with cell towers when the plane is in the air," Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to look into the issue recommended last month that the government allow greater use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure has been mounting on the FAA to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics, such as Missouri Democratic Sen. Claire McCaskill, argue that there are no security reasons for the bans.
Compliance with the restrictions is also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore instructions to turn off their devices.
The FAA began restricting passengers' use of electronic devices in 1966 in response to reports of interference with navigation and communication equipment, when passengers began carrying FM radios, high-tech gadgets of the time.
The new airliners are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also developed and approved by the FAA as resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers the use of Wi-Fi at cruising altitude for several years.
Planes modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of liners are adapted for increased use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices typically emit much lower power radio signals than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, emit only minimal signals when flipping pages.
But signals become more powerful when devices download or send data.
Among those who sought to ease restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers was the company Amazon.com.
In 2011, the company loaded an entire airliner with its Kindle e-book reader and flew it to check for problems, but never found them.
Members of the FAA advisory committee expressed mixed feelings about whether the use of the devices posed any risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Air Passenger Association said he believes interference from the devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other members of the committee said there were only isolated reports from pilots confirming that the devices could interfere with aviation systems, and most of those messages were very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to require passengers to disable devices during landings on instruments in limited visibility.
