New anti-anti-polio vaccine may deprive the process of smoking pleasure
Scientists have developed an anti-silicon vaccine that could deprive the process of smoking cigarettes pleasure.
One dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine dependence for life.
Further tests are needed before human trials begin, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the first results were encouraging.
"We very much hope that this vaccine strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit by trying all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine dependence is strong enough to overcome it with these modern remedies," Professor Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been designed to carry genetic information to produce anti-silicon antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a steady stream of antibodies.
Antibodies track down any nicotine molecules in the blood, neutralizing them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting a nicotine strike.
In the tests, vaccinated mice, which were subsequently given nicotine, continued their normal activities.
And mice who weren't given the vaccine "relaxed, and this is a sign that nicotine has reached their brains," the researchers said.
These experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
To maintain a high level of antibodies, injections had to be done so often that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if the future human vaccine were completely safe, it could be given to children before they wanted to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
But it is more likely that it will be used by smokers to quit.
"They'll know that if they start smoking again, they won't enjoy it because of the nicotine vaccine, and it might help them get rid of that habit," he said.
