Agency "Rosbalt" deprived of media status for swearing
On October 31, the Moscow City Court decided to invalidate the registration license of the agency "Rosbalt" - Lenta writes.
Roskomnadzor insisted on depriving the agency of media status for systematic and gross violations of the law on mass media.
During the trial, an unpleasant precedent was created: the court considered it possible to close the media, effectively denying the publication the right to put forward counter-arguments.
What is "Rosbalt"
The Rosbalt News Agency was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In the following years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional units.
The agency also has offices in the former Soviet Union.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has developed and functioned as a federal information and analysis agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was one of the most recognizable private Internet media in Russia.
At the same time, "Rosbalt" has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of exclusive publications of the agency were (and still make up) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talks about the proximity of the publication to the security forces continued throughout the existence of the agency.
In addition to the fact that Rosbalt had an extensive database of sources in various departments, in favor of such assumptions was said by the fact that the project was headed by Natalia Chaplina - the wife of Viktor Cherkesov.
At the same time, Chaplin's role in the management of "Rosbalt" is not completely clear: most often it is called "project manager".
The director general of the agency is Larissa Afonina, the editor-in-chief is Nikolai Ulyanov.
Recently, "Rosbalt" did not appear in the ratings of the federal media - neither by citation, nor by audience.
In October, the agency took the 25th place in the ranking of attendance sites of Russian media according to LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of the site rosbalt.ru is about 150,000 unique visitors (and up to 500,000 views), monthly - about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials for the last five months - notes about the kremlin's helplessness in relations with Ukraine, the death of the lead singer of the group "King and jester", pogroms in the capital Biryulev.
Rosbalt's conflict with Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when amendments to the law on mass media came into force, banning journalists from swearing.
The agency found the banned vocabulary in two videos published on the agency's website ("Jigit from Krasnodar" and "Pussy Riot desecrated oil rigs").
Further sides describe in different ways.
Roskomnadzor on the basis of the discovered videos accused "Rosbalt" of gross and systematic violation of the law on mass media and appealed to the court with a demand to take away the agency's license.
"Rosbalt" stated that the claims of the agency are wrong: first, the videos were not editorial materials, secondly, the mother words in them were disguised, and, thirdly, immediately after the warning the videos were removed from the site.
Representatives of the agency appealed Roskomnadzor's claims to the world court - and when the Moscow City Court accepted Roskomnadzor's claim on October 22, 2013, the consideration of these complaints was still ongoing.
However, on the 25th the magistrate decided not in favor of "Rosbalt": editor-in-chief Nikolai Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the code on administrative offenses and fined 20,000 rubles - 10,000 for each video.
Obviously, this predetermined the outcome of the hearing in the Moscow City Court - if we abandon the idea that the outcome could have been a foregone conclusion even earlier.
On October 31, the court decided to invalidate Rosbalt's registration certificate, effectively depriving the agency of media status.
It cannot be said that Rosbalt was left alone during this confrontation.
The agency was supported by the State Duma deputies (the statement to the head of Roskomnadzor, Aleksandr Sharov, was signed by 26 deputies on October 10; the document itself was submitted at the initiative of the Communist Party).
The head of the Union of Journalists of Russia Vsevolod Bogdanov, the chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists Pavel Gusev and the head of the Presidential Human Rights Council Mikhail Fedotov claimed that the closure of the newspaper was illegal.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, the leadership of Roskomnadzor even provided him with some guarantees that it would not come to the revocation of the license.
The trial of Rosbalt showed that under whose jurisdiction it is safer to be the media in Russia today - a big question.
