And so old that it turned into a fossil: I first heard a "duck" that "independence means passport control" at least 40 years ago.
And yet there is an interesting moment lost in the retelling of an old fairy tale.
Why should an independent Scotland comply with the orders of Europe?
Why change the yoke of London to the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
Here's the real European news: the great postwar plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With the European crisis, the "Europe" project is officially dead.
Across the European Union, parties opposed to the EU or the abolition of the euro as a single currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party - founded only this year - came out of nowhere and won nearly five million votes in September's federal election, effectively ousting the Free Democrats (similar to our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been internal opposition to the plan for the creation of a federal Europe.
Nevertheless, the current economic crisis has been a turning point.
The austerity measures imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the shackles imposed on national economies through the preservation of the single currency, have led many people to believe that the "Europe" project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with the fact that national governments operate with excessive budget deficits - this was only true for Greece.
In fact, the Eurosystem has blocked its members on exchange rates favorable to German exporters - which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe finds itself at a predetermined disadvantage in terms of production opportunities compared to Germany.
The only saving means is to cut salaries and government spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
Behind the current problems of the budget and currency is a deeper problem of Europe's productive abilities.
As a result of a set of green energy measures introduced by Brussels - a cipher that means subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer - European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as in the United States.
This is a paralyzingly unfavourable price environment, as we have seen in Grangemouth.
No wage freeze in the world will stop the crushing victory of cheap US shale gas over the European petrochemical industry.
As a result, a revolt is brewing, especially in France, once the most ardent supporter of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on a par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of gaining political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving France's shattered economy in distress.
The result is that Marine Le Pen's anti-EU National Front party has just won a crucial by-election, dropping the ruling Socialist Party into third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 per cent of the vote - a timely warning to British Labour that there is no suggestion that a split among the right will automatically affect the left.
What does Le Pen do with her newfound popularity among the French white working class?
She wants to use next year's EU elections to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against the single currency.
If - and this is very likely - anti-EU parties gain support in this election, such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament for the first time.
Here is my opinion: soon the growing mood against the EU and against the single currency in Europe will merge together to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will again become something of a vague "Europe (sovereign) nation" that General de Gaulle liked.
Germany and several dependent economies may keep the euro, but France and southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I assume that the UK is distancing itself from this project, hoping to get closer to the US.
Nevertheless, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific indicates that the UK will be left unattended in the cold Atlantic.
In what position does this leave Scotland?
We can choose to become a region (in fact) of Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which means, among other things, sending Berlin and Brussels to hell.
I suspect that Scotland will be able to succeed under a freer European agreement provided that we keep our currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries will be easier in non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider repeating Norway's experience and maintaining our economic independence.
The Scottish National Party government in Scotland is, oddly enough, the most successful political movement in Europe against austerity measures, which won an impressive majority in 2011 thanks to objections to spending cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor of the Exchequer Alistair Darling and the subsequent coalition of the Tories and Liberal Democrats.
It would be ludicrous for Scotland to vote for independence now just to adopt the austerity measures imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
