Should a mother be frightened if her daughter begins to form breast rudiments and grow pubic hair at 7 or 8 years old?
At the American Academy of Pediatrics' annual conference this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new norm.
"I spend a lot of time reassuring my parents - it doesn't usually mean that full puberty is fast," Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight shift in the age of menarche (the first menstruation) over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years and down from 12.75 in 1970.
"After the breast begins to develop, it takes at least two to three years to menarche," said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of "Early Puberty in Girls: How to Cope With This Common Problem."
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will progress.
Discussions are under way about what constitutes actual puberty, but is considered "premature" when breast augmentation is accompanied by a sharp increase in growth up to 8 years.
In most cases, the process will slow down or pause - something that the pediatrician can monitor closely.
Faster progression may be grounds for analysis by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are procedures to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature bone aging, which can eventually lead to slower growth and low growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormone therapy are based on the child's age, development level, growth rates and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplovitz is careful with medications, but admits that "suppression of puberty can alleviate behavioral problems and girls' feelings that they are different from their peers."
Another big problem is clear: parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
"They're worried about the risk of pregnancy or even how they're going to handle hygiene issues," Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock," recalls one woman, whose daughter started menstruating when she was 10.
Although there were signs and we talked about menstruation, she wasn't emotionally ready.
She came home from school scared and upset that she was the first among her friends.
There are many advertised theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
In boys - as in girls - puberty comes earlier.
Kaplovitz argues that the premise that weighs the most is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped to conduct a study of girls aged 6 to 9, which links the amount of fat in the body with puberty.
Other evidence supports this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers.
There are various explanations.
Worldwide, early puberty is likely to be influenced by everything from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: although boys have facial and pubic hair appearing at a younger age, the trend towards full early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference confirmed the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair occurs even in infants and toddlers.
"We have to be careful about how we define true puberty," said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Gorieb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to receive guidance from a pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"This could mean an earlier-than-expected conversation," Kaplovitz explained.
If you stay calm, your child will usually react well.
Girls who bloom early need confirmation that even when it happens earlier than expected, this process is a normal part of life.
