RBS suspends two currency traders
Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders in its foreign exchange division, according to two people familiar with the situation, further confirming that global regulators are investigating alleged currency market manipulation.
Some of the world's biggest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, have confirmed they are cooperating with regulators in investigations into the world's largest financial market, with a daily turnover of $5.3 trillion.
The two traders will be the first RBS employees suspended in the unfolding investigation, which echoes the LIBOR interbank rate manipulation scandal.
Refusing to comment on the suspension, the bank confirmed that it had received requests for information from regulators this month.
"Our ongoing investigation into this matter is ongoing and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and our other regulators," the bank said two weeks ago.
Last month, whistleblowers said RBS had handed over email and instant messages it had received and sent to its former trader, the UK's regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA).
This trader, Richard Usher, left RBS in 2010 and, as far as is understood, he was granted leave in his current position as head of European spot currency trading at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, head of European spot trading at Citi, went on leave this week, while Matt Gardiner, a former senior currency trader at Barclays and UBS, was suspended by Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders has been charged with any wrongdoing.
Mr. Usher's instant messaging team included bankers from Barclays and Citigroup, according to whistleblowers.
UBS Bank said this week that it had taken action against some of its employees after Swiss regulator Finma said it was investigating alleged currency market manipulation in a number of Swiss banks.
At least six regulators around the world - the European Commission, Finma, Switzerland's antitrust authority Weko, fca, the U.S. Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority - are reviewing allegations that bankers colluded to influence the foreign exchange market.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also launched internal audits or received requests for information from regulators, officials familiar with the situation said.
Banks have been reviewing instant messages and emails for years in search of wrongdoing.
News of the audits has stirred up traders in the sector of activity, which in recent years has been one of the largest sources of income of trading divisions of investment banks, which this year, however, faced difficulties because low currency volatility reduces favorable opportunities for resellers.
Some bankers have tried to downplay the gravity of the situation, saying that the vast and highly liquid currency market is almost impossible to manipulate, but senior traders say this is not always true.
According to the senior trader, despite the huge volume of daily trading in the foreign exchange market, the fragmentation of liquidity between different trading platforms and the increased use by banks of their internal platforms means that "you can start to influence the market at a very small price".
The news came on the same day that Credit Suisse announced it had fired one of its stock trading backers on the London Stock Exchange this week after it caused a loss of nearly $6 million late last year.
The bank immediately notified the relevant authorities and is cooperating with its regulators.
"We are confident that the trader acted alone and that this matter has been localized," Credit Suisse said.
