Is there a black box in your car?
While American road planners are trying to find money to repair the crumbling system of highways, many begin to see the solution in a small black box neatly attached to the dashboard of your car.
These devices, which track every mile a motorist pass and pass this information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt to modernize America's outdated highway finance system by planned authorities in Washington and the state.
Usually the boring arena of highway planning has suddenly spawned intense debate and racy alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups in lobbying for the government to use small boxes to track the number of miles you drive and even possibly where you drive them - and then use that information in tax bills.
The tea party movement is in shock.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and raises a number of privacy issues.
And while Congress can't yet agree on whether to continue or not, several states are not going to wait.
They ponder how over the next decade it is possible to move to a system where drivers pay for every mile of the road they drive.
Thousands of motorists have already taken to testing these black boxes, some of which have a satellite tracking function.
This is really necessary for our country.
"This is not an issue on which we can have a choice," said Hassan Ihrata, executive director of the Southern California Government Association, which is preparing plans to begin tracking the state's miles by every California motorist by 2025.
There will be changes in the way we pay these taxes.
The technology for this is already there.
This is compounded by the lack of funds from the Government's Highway Fund, which is funded by taxes that Americans pay at gas stations.
Americans are no longer buying as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars drive more miles per gallon.
The federal tax itself, 18.4 cents per gallon, has not been raised in 20 years.
Politicians do not want to raise the tax even by one cent at high gasoline prices.
"The gasoline tax is simply impossible to maintain," said Lee Mannich, a transportation policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed 500 tracking devices on cars to test the pay system.
"It will be the best alternative in the long run," he said.
The nerds call it a pardon board.
Unsurprisingly, the idea is attracting urban liberals because taxes could change the nature of travel to reduce congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
Planners in California are eyeing the system as they develop strategies to meet the targets set by the state's ambitious laws to combat global warming.
But Rep. Bill Schuster ( Republican, Pennsylvania), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he, too, sees the system as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free market supporters at Reason are also thrilled to make drivers pay for every mile.
"It's not just a tax that's going to go into a black hole," said Adrian Moore, vice president of political affairs at Reason.
People directly pay for what they get.
The move is also supported by two former U.S. transportation ministers who in 2011 called on Congress to move toward a pay-per-view.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have involved about 10,000 vehicles.
But House leaders rejected the proposal because of concerns from rural legislators representing voters who often travel miles to work or the city in everyday life.
Several states and cities, however, are following this path on their own.
The greatest enthusiasm is evident in Oregon, where 5,000 drivers are involved in the largest experiment in the country.
These drivers will soon be paying the state for miles of mileage instead of a gasoline tax.
In Nevada, the pilot project has already been completed.
In New York it is considered.
Illinois will test it on a limited basis involving trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transportation departments of 17 East Coast states (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is looking at how they can implement these changes.
This concept has not been universally accepted.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer cars were recently fitted with these devices, drivers were concerned that the government could track their every move.
"Concerns about big brother and things like that are a big problem," said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn't what people wanted.
As the tests were well underway, the Nevada Chapter de La Disenfranchis, warned on its website, "It will be easy to turn these devices into full-scale tracking devices."
There is no need to build a huge, cumbersome technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to record the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of several states that are working hard to find low-cost technology that would allow state authorities to keep records of miles of driving, but without information about location and time.
If you can do that, Khan said, society will feel more relaxed.
The search for this technology led some state agencies to a small young company in California called True Mileage.
Initially, the company did not assist in collecting state taxes.
It sought to enter the emerging market of the type of car insurance, in which drivers pay on the basis of mileage.
But the devices it tests attract road planners because they don't use GPS and provide a limited amount of information that is periodically downloaded using the modem.
"People will be more inclined to do this if you don't track their speed and track their location," said Ryan Morrison, chief executive of True Mileage.
There were some big mistakes in some of these state pilot programs.
There are far less expensive and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with providing drivers with different options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they can opt out of the device altogether, opting instead to pay a flat fee based on the average number of miles that all residents of the state travel.
Elsewhere they hope to sell the idea to the wary public by forcing the devices to do more, not less.
In New York, transportation officials are seeking to develop a tax-free device that will also accept payment for parking meters, provide "pay as you drive" insurance, and collect a pool of real-time speed data from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
"Motorists will be attracted to participate by the benefit that they will be offered," reads the document of urban design.
Some transport system planners, however, wonder whether all the talk of pay is just a huge distraction.
The City Transportation Commission in the San Francisco Bay Area officials say Congress could very simply overcome the bankruptcy of the Highway Construction Trust by raising gasoline taxes.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be levied on hybrid car drivers and other persons whose vehicles do not use much petrol to pay their fair share.
"There's no need for radical surgery when all you have to do is take aspirin," said Randy Rentschler, director of the Law and Public Relations Commission.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers will worry about their privacy and a lot of other things.
