Syria destroys its chemical weapons production, says monitoring group
Syria has destroyed basic equipment for the production of chemical weapons and munitions with poison gas, an international monitoring group said on Thursday, while violent clashes raged in the north of the country, near one of the sites believed to contain toxic substances.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group said more than 120,000 people had been killed since the country's civil war began nearly three years ago.
The statement by the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons was made one day before
the 1 November deadline set by this Hague-based organization for Damascus to destroy or "inoperable" all chemical weapons production facilities and mechanisms to mix chemicals with the receipt of poison gas and fill in munitions.
The completion of what is essentially the initial stage of destruction is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable that aims to destroy all of Damascus' chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of equipment means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
Nevertheless, Damascus has yet to begin destroying existing weapons and stockpiles.
The country is believed to have about 1,000 metric tons of chemicals and weapons, including mustard gas and sarin nerve gas.
The announcement came during fierce fighting on Thursday in the city of Safira, which experts say is home to a chemical weapons facility as well as storage sites, according to the Britain-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights.
An activist group that tracked casualties through a network of activists in Syria said on Thursday that 120,296 people had been killed.
Of this number, 61,067 were said to be civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the government's side, the group said, 29,954 are members of President Bashar al-Assad's armed forces, 18,678 are pro-government fighters and 187 are Lebanese Hezbollah fighters.
Also among the dead, according to the statement, were 2,202 army defectors and about 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
The UN estimates of 25 July that 100,000 have died in the conflict since March 2011.
This figure has not been updated since then.
The conflict has forced some 2 million people to flee the country.
Assad's forces have been battling rebels in Safir for weeks, many of them linked to al-qaeda groups.
The center said Thursday there were casualties on both sides, but gave no specifics.
The fighting underscored the danger faced by chemical weapons inspectors, driven by the tight deadlines of their mission to rid Syria of its toxic arsenal, at the height of the ongoing civil war.
In a statement, the OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, said its team was "now satisfied that it has verified and seen all critical production facilities and mixing/refueling equipment destroyed by Syria."
She added that "no additional inspection activities are currently planned."
Earlier this week, inspectors said they had completed the first round of verification work by visiting 21 of the 23 sites claimed by Damascus.
They were unable to visit the two sites for security reasons, the inspectors said.
On Thursday, the OPCW said both sites were, according to Syria, "abandoned and ... the items of the chemical weapons programme in them have been moved to other declared locations that have been inspected."
It was not immediately clear whether the Safir site was one of two sites that OPCW inspectors were unable to visit.
Syria has submitted a plan for the total destruction of its chemical weapons, which is due to be approved next month by the OPCW Executive Committee.
"I applaud the courage and bravery that you have all demonstrated in carrying out the most difficult mission this organization has ever undertaken," said Ahmet Uzyumju, Director General of the Observatory Group, in a commentary published by the OPCW.
For the third year, the civil war has pitted rebels, mostly Sunni Muslims, against Assad's government and its security forces, which are made up of members of his Alawite sect, an offshoot of Shiite Islam.
As for other events, the head of the center Rami Abdurrahman said there was a strong explosion on Wednesday at an air defense facility in Syria's coastal province of Latakia.
The cause of the explosion is unknown, he said.
Report: Obama campaign considers excluding Biden in favor of Hillary Clinton
According to The New York Times, President Barack Obama's closest advisers were secretly considering replacing Vice President Joe Biden with Hillary Clinton on the 2012 election list.
This discovery is the brightest sensation of all the expected books by Mark Halperin and John Hailemann about the 2012 campaign "Betting Doubled: The Game Changed 2012."
The Times obtained a copy of the forthcoming book and reported Thursday night that the president's closest aides conducted "large-scale research in focus groups and opinion polls in late 2011" to assess whether Biden's exclusion could help raise fading hopes for Obama's re-election.
According to The Times political commentator Jonathan Martin, the book provides a detailed description of the efforts of senior campaign and White House officials, namely former White House chief of staff Bill Daly, to assess the impact on the vote of former Secretary clinton's appointment as vice president.
The possible replacement was a secret carefully guarded in the Chicago campaign headquarters and in the Oval Office.
Only six of the president's closest advisers - including Daley, former Obama campaign chief Jim Messina and former senior White House advisers David Axelrod and David Plouffe - knew a replacement was under consideration.
The book " Doubles Stakes" claims that Daley was the initiator of an attempt to replace Biden despite their "close personal relationship," but ultimately abandoned the move when their data showed that adding Clinton to the polls would not "significantly improve Obama's chances."
In an interview with Martin, Daley confirmed that the administration was indeed considering replacing Biden with Clinton.
"I was very vocal in my support for a lot of things, and that was one of them," Daley told the newspaper.
You have to remember that the president was in terrible shape at the time, so we thought, "Oh my God, what are we going to do?"
While Daley described the study as a "necessary test," Martin told CNN's Anderson Cooper that the campaign had invested heavily in examining whether the move would pay dividends on the vote.
"Election headquarters don't spend that amount of money on polls and focus groups unless they take something seriously," Martin said on the AK 360 program.
It is unclear, however, whether Obama knew his team was exploring the possibility of a replacement.
Martin told CNN that he asked Daley if his then-boss knew about a possible reshuffle.
While Daley said he didn't think the president "was aware" of a possible replacement, the former chief of staff acknowledged that it was "possible" Obama knew.
Martin added that the "double stakes" did not give a clear answer to the question of whether the results of the political probe had reached Obama's desk.
Cooper asked Martin if he seriously believed obama was unaware of the study of the possibility of removing Biden from the polls.
"Maybe," Martin replied.
