Legislative bans forced Russians to drink less beer
Russian brewers are in a bad mood.
According to their estimates, the consumption of beer in the country next year will remain at the same level, and this is at best.
Although businessmen initially expected to grow.
After all, this year is not bad for them: sales fell by 7 percent.
The head of one of the largest brewing companies in the country, The Chairman of the Council of the Union of Russian Brewers Isaac Sheps, told about all this at the third annual conference of the Adam Smith Institute "Commodities of Everyday Demand in Russia", which has just ended in Moscow.
It discussed the state regulation of the market.
From 2008 to 2012, the Russian beer market has already decreased by 18 percent, as in recent years the country has seen a significant increase in regulation of the brewing industry in terms of the production and turnover of beer - a drink with a low alcohol content - told the audience Sheps.
No country in the world has such a strict restriction of the beer market, unpredictable introduction of more and more illogical bans, which are justified by the alleged fight against alcohol abuse.
Brewer lamented that many legislative prohibitions designed to reduce alcohol abuse have little impact, but new initiatives are constantly emerging.
The ban on selling alcohol in kiosks was the hardest hit by beer producers.
"We immediately lost 35,000 consumers," Said Isaac Shepps.
Brewers have two forecasts for next year.
Optimistic - the one that Sheps said: sales of foam drink will remain at the same level.
Pessimistic - will fall by another 2-3 percent.
To keep their profits, businessmen are forced to move away from varieties designed for the mass consumer, in the class of "premium": beer will be less, but it will cost more.
Meanwhile, the radical consequences of falling sales with a small amount of alcohol are not yet visible.
"According to my observations, the level of alcoholism remains at about the same level," said alexey Sotnikov, a narcologist.
However, the proportion of patients who drink strong drinks surrogates, as well as those who are "hooked" on alcohol-containing tonic drinks like "Jaguar" has increased, whereas ten years ago it was the "beer" alcoholism that prevailed.
