Bombardier's profit falls as shipments fall and plane orders fall
Bombardier Corp., the Canadian manufacturer of planes and trains, reported on Thursday a 15 percent decline in net profit due to a decline in third-quarter orders and deliveries and contract problems at its rail division.
Montreal-based Bombardier also did not release any flight test data for its newest CSeries aircraft, nor did it provide new information on whether ambitious plans to commercialize the aircraft would be implemented by next September.
After the first flight of the prototype aircraft, which took place about a month and a half ago, it flew only three more times, raising questions about whether the test stage is on schedule.
The results fell short of forecasts and led to a drop of more than 8 percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, downgraded his valuation on Thursday from "above the market average" to "mid-market" because of the belief that share growth is limited in the next quarter or two.
"While the decline in aircraft deliveries was generally predictable, we are certainly disappointed with the transport department's profit figures," Doerksen said in a stock market review.
We believe that Bombardier will receive new orders for CSeries as the flight test program continues.
However, unless new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more skeptical of the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will allow it to gain a place in the lower price segment of the market, which is now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first prototype aircraft was unveiled in March and flew for the first time in September after months of delay.
However, there are not too many solid orders for the CSeries, as potential buyers wait for the results of flight tests to test the company's claims about fuel efficiency and the potential cost-effectiveness of the new liner.
In total, there are now 403 orders and agreements with 15 customers and operators.
Chief executive Pierre Baudouin was confident that Bombardier would reach its target of 300 solid orders by the time the first aircraft was put into commercial operation.
On Thursday, executives also assured analysts and the media that the program was moving forward as planned.
"The test model of the aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected," Baudouan said during a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates were planned for the plane's downtime.
All manufacturers plan the tests differently.
We decided to take the first flight and take a break for upgrades, so we did.
This will happen throughout the flight testing program.
The second of the five test samples is due to fly in the coming weeks and all others will soon follow, the company said.
Still, analysts are skeptical that the first customer will be able to start operating the CSeries 12 months after its maiden flight.
Bombardier said it was assessing the timing of the commissioning and would provide new information in the next few months.
"This slow pace of flight testing - although likely in line with Bombardier's internal schedule - reinforces our view that commissioning will be rescheduled for the first quarter of 2015," Doerksen said.
In the third quarter ended September 30, Bombardier's net income fell to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, last year.
Adjusted earnings per share remained the same at 9 cents.
Gross revenue fell slightly, from $4.2 billion to $4.1 billion.
Analysts had expected earnings of 10 cents per share and gross revenue of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
The world's fourth-largest aircraft maker said it delivered 45 aircraft in the quarter, down from 57 the previous year.
The total number of orders fell from 83 to 26 aircraft.
The aerospace department's order portfolio was $32.9 billion as of September 30, unchanged from December 31.
"In the aerospace field, the results were in line with our objectives, but the low number of incoming orders and overall market conditions were an unpleasant factor," Baudouan said.
Gross revenue for aerospace fell 13 percent to $2 billion.
Bombardier, the world's largest train maker, said gross revenue in the sector rose nearly 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
The portfolio of orders in the transport division was $32.6 billion as of September 30, which is slightly higher than the figure from December 31.
The revenues of the transport division were negatively affected by problems with the performance of several large contracts.
Management said a new development plan would be unveiled in the fourth quarter.
Shares of Bombardier, which also announced that Google Chief Financial Officer Patrick Pichette will join the board, fell 8.5 percent to C$4.83 in mid-Thursday trading.
Brazilian company Embraer SA, the world's third-largest commercial aircraft manufacturer and Bombardier's closest competitor, reported a 10 percent decline in quarterly revenue on Thursday.
