Two YMCA officers have been charged with sexual offences before being charged against Jonathan Lord, the Royal Commission has revealed
Two YMCA NSW officers were charged with child sex offences before charges were brought in 2011 against Child care worker Jonathan Lord in Caringbach, the Royal Commission into Child Sexual Abuse has said.
But the commission's opening statement said it had "never dealt with cases of child sexual abuse within her organization."
Chief executive Philip Hare was asked about one case in which an YMCA employee was charged with child pornography offences and another case in which a gym instructor at YMCA Caringbah Hall was convicted of sexual offences against children under his care in 1991.
Mr Hare told Gail Furness, the counsel assisting the commission, that he was aware of the first case but was not aware of the second.
He acknowledged that the YMCA also made inaccuracies in its opening speech to the commission, claiming that "there were external checks by the YMCA that recognised that the YMCA was at the forefront of child safety."
Evidence submitted to the commission indicates that the YMCA has been notified that it has received the second of four possible quality audits from the End of the Department of Education and Communities in August this year.
Mr Hare, who joined the YMCA when he was 21, admitted that he and the lower management had made a mistake in hiring lord and had failed to ensure staff had a clear understanding of their obligations to report child safety breaches.
Earlier this year Lorde was convicted of sexual offences against 12 boys during his two years at the YMCA.
He was jailed for a minimum of six years.
But Mr Hare rejected the suggestion that the YMCA's corporate ethics had prevented staff from reporting lord's child safety breaches.
Officers testified that they had witnessed abuses, including the fact that Lorde was alone with the children, personally cared for them, put them on their knees, said he loved one of them and allowed them to play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Oakwell, who was under the Lord's leadership and asked for her to be trained in child protection because she was concerned about his behaviour, testified that she found Jackie Barnat, child care manager at the YMCA's Caringbah branch, who was lord's leader, "very intimidating and often difficult to access."
The Executive Director said he did not accept staff's explanation that they were embarrassed to report the situation to their superiors.
Rather, he said, their friendship with Lorde led them away from the idea of having to report him.
Mr Hare said he had presented to the YMCA board of New South Wales his view that the lesson for the organisation from the "Jonathan Lord incident" was not "concerned with providing information" from staff and the council agreed with him.
Mr Hare said the decision to force staff to sign confidentiality agreements shortly after the allegations emerged was made by YMCA director-general of child custody Liam Wheatley.
He said it was intended to prevent the damage to evidence, but was "overzealous" and the decision was poorly implemented.
The YMCA of New South Wales was not a child-friendly organisation during Jonathan Lord's tenure between 2009 and 2011, child molestation expert Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University told the commission.
He said there were "serious problems" in recruiting, selecting, instructing, training and monitoring staff.
The hearing has been adjourned until December 20.
