Ben Greenman: The Tenth Anniversary of the New York Comedy Festival: The New Yorker
It is safe to say that New York is the birthplace of stand-up comedy in America: almost a hundred years ago, entertainer Frank Fay, who worked as an entertainer at the Palace Theatre on Broadway, began to tell jokes directly to the public in a colloquial manner.
Fay's innovation was eventually picked up by others, most recently the New York Comedy Festival.
Created and curated by Caroline Hirsch, founder of the stand-up club Carolines, the festival celebrates its tenth anniversary this year, with more than sixty shows in small clubs and large theatres.
"Most of these headliners started at Carolines and then achieved more success, reached a level where they were too famous to play for the club," Hirsch said.
We created this festival as a way to continue working with them.
This year's event includes performances by Wanda Sykes, Kathy Griffin and Bill Mara, as well as "Stand for Heroes, an annual musical and comedy benefit concert for military veterans at Madison Square Garden, which will feature bruce Springsteen, Jon Stewart, Roger Waters and Bill Cosby.
With the expansion of the festival, the world of comedy has expanded.
Several comedians participating in this year's festival have gained popularity in an unconventional way, for example through shows on small TV channels like Comedy Central, FX and Spike.
Nick Kroll gained notoriety for his role in a comedy series on a little-known cable channel (deliberately scrubbing FXX's "League" on fantasy football), and now hosts his own sketch show on Comedy Central.
Jenny Slate joined the cast on both "Saturday Night Live" and "Parks and Recreation Areas," though she's best known for the viral series "Marseille - Shell in Boots."
Both Kroll and Slate, like other young comedians with original style (the surreally pessimistic Anthony Jeselnik, sly, racially focused by Kamau Bell), are the result of the decentralized world of American comedy.
One of the highlights of the festival will be David Steinberg's interview with Larry David.
Steinberg began as a stand-up comedian, but later became a successful director on television and in film, as well as an unofficial comedy historian.
From 2005 to 2007, he was the host of a TV Land show called Sit Down Comedy with David Steinberg.
The meeting will take place in the Town Hall in midtown Manhattan.
"This city is definitely a central element of all of Larry's work," Steinberg said.
He told me that when he came here, he sometimes walks down a street between two houses and thinks, "If I'm left without money at all, maybe I'll live here."
